   	<li class="clear" id="comment-57204">
    	<div class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 clear">
	   		<div class="col140">
	   				   			<p>by <strong><a href='http://www.kmareka.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Nancy Green</a></strong></p>
	   			<p><strong>25 Aug 2010</strong> at <a href="#comment-57204">04:33</a></p>
	   				   				   		</div>
	   		
	   		<div class="col460 clear">
	       		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/77124c13a84fc26dd989ba1cd21dd0c7?s=50&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D50&amp;r=X' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />	   				   			<p>thanks for writing this, MayMay. I want to mention that I first met Tara Hurley at the Coalition Against Human Trafficking. She said to me that she doesn&#8217;t think selling sex in the spas is a good way to make a living, despite the temptation to make a lot of money fast.<br />
 I notice that the one I drive past on my way to work is still open.<br />
To really address trafficking we will need to invest in identifying and convicting anyone who uses force, fraud or coercion to deprive another person of their freedom to seek justice or to simply walk away. That person might be the &#8216;illegal&#8217; working in a restaurant or factory, or the American who has gotten involved in a situation they can&#8217;t get out of.<br />
 I have serious disagreements with people who say &#8216;sex positive&#8217; means that selling access to your body is no more significant than telemarketing or working at a low wage job. But to me that&#8217;s a matter for persuasion, and far less a priority than the problem of exploitation of vulnerable people, especially in a global economy turning increasingly desperate.<br />
 If the arrest of women in the spas turns out to be the salvation Dr. Hughes and her supporters claim then I will be glad to be wrong. If she is actively working with the ACI to offer social services to the women her lobbying helped &#8216;rescue&#8217; I&#8217;d like to know about it.<br />
 We&#8217;ll soon have a new mayor and a new governor. I don&#8217;t know if we will be able to make our state less corrupt, but we have to try. How laws are enforced will determine whether the anti-trafficking bill of 2007 is ever used.</p>
	   		</div>
   		</div>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
